{\bf Language Models as Knowledge Bases.}
The LAMA project [petroni2019language] posed
the hypothesis that probing LMs with cloze questions is a powerful way of extracting structured facts from the latently represented corpus on which the LM was trained. A suite of follow-up works pursued this theme
further and devised improvements and extensions
(e.g., [heinzerling2021language,jiang2020x,kassner2020negated,roberts2020much,shin2020autoprompt,DBLP:conf/naacl/ZhongFC21]).
This gave rise to the notion of ``prompt engineering'' for all kinds of NLP tasks [DBLP:journals/corr/abs-2107-13586].